          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My acquisition includes multi-year earnout. How is that treated?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Acquisition earnout payments tied to revenue or EBITDA milestones qualify under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-09</a> as continuing other sources with documented payment schedule. We document the acquisition agreement, earnout structure, milestone tracking through current performance, and multi-year payment schedule. Earnout treatment depends on payment certainty and continuing duration.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for a founder mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on stage. Bootstrapped sole prop: two complete 1040s with Schedule C, 1099-NECs, business bank statements. S-corp / partnership founder: Form 1120-S or Form 1065 with K-1s for 2 years, Schedule L, S-corp election or partnership agreement. VC-funded founder-CEO: two W-2s, current pay stubs, HR letter from company, equity grant documentation with vesting schedule. Post-exit: acquisition agreement, earnout schedule, brokerage statements showing liquid balance, Section 1202 QSBS documentation if applicable. Florida no-state-income-tax residency documented for tax optimization narrative.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Should I incorporate as C-corp or S-corp / LLC for tax optimization?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on exit expectation. C-corp incorporation enables Section 1202 QSBS treatment (up to $10M or 10x basis tax-free on qualifying founder stock held 5+ years) but exposes profits to double-taxation at corporate level + dividend distribution level. S-corp / LLC pass-through structures avoid double-taxation but don&rsquo;t enable QSBS. Coordinate with your CPA early. For startups expecting eventual large exit ($5M+), C-corp with QSBS structure commonly optimal. For lifestyle businesses without exit expectation, S-corp / LLC commonly preferable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for founders?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; mortgage rates for founders are the same as for any other borrower at the same credit profile, loan amount, and program selection. Conventional Conforming and Jumbo achieve standard pricing. Non-QM products (Bank Statement, Asset-Depletion, P&amp;L Only) carry rate premium reflecting the specialty underwriting framework but aren&rsquo;t founder-specific.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My business income varies year-over-year. How does 24-month averaging treat that?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> for Schedule C and <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a> for S-corp / partnership, the 24-month average smooths year-over-year variation. For growth-stage businesses with substantial recent revenue increase vs prior year, the average may understate current capacity &mdash; P&amp;L Statement Only Non-QM provides alternative qualifying on current YTD performance.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I make S-corp election as a bootstrapped founder?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically at $150K-$200K+ annual net Schedule C income for bootstrapped solo founders, S-corp election starts producing meaningful self-employment tax savings under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1361" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 1361</a>. S-corp involves paying W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $80K-$150K for solo founders depending on business and personal labor contribution) and taking remaining net as K-1 distributions. Coordinate with your CPA for compensation reasonableness analysis.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My VC-funded company is approaching IPO. How should I time my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Approaching IPO creates complex timing options: (1) close mortgage BEFORE IPO using established VC-funded founder-CEO W-2 history; (2) close AFTER IPO post-lockup using stock sale liquidity for Asset-Depletion path; (3) coordinate with anticipated secondary tender offer timing. Most founders close before IPO using W-2 history since post-IPO lockup (typically 6 months) delays liquidity availability.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse has W-2 stability while I&rsquo;m founder. Does that help?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Substantially yes &mdash; spouse W-2 stability provides strong qualifying anchor for founder households where founder income is variable or below-market. Combined household income from spouse stable W-2 + founder Schedule C / W-2 typically produces robust qualifying capacity. Both files combine as co-borrowers with channel-appropriate analysis (B3-3.1-01 spouse W-2 + B3-3.3-02 or B3-3.4-02 founder income).</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders sometimes refuse founder files?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Six reasons: (1) bootstrapped Schedule C high deductions misread as profitability problem without Form 1084 cash-flow addback application; (2) S-corp founder W-2 reasonable comp treated as ceiling without recognizing K-1 distribution as continuing income; (3) VC-funded founder-CEO below-market W-2 treated as ceiling without recognizing equity participation; (4) pre-IPO secondary share sale proceeds refused as "non-recurring"; (5) acquisition earnout refused as "contingent future"; (6) post-exit founders qualified on reduced W-2 without Asset-Depletion path on substantial liquid reserves. The income and asset capacity is documentable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company received tier-1 VC funding. Does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">VC funding status (Series A through D and beyond from tier-1 VC firms like Sequoia, Andreessen Horowitz, Benchmark, Accel, Greylock, Lightspeed, Founders Fund, Bessemer) supports company narrative but doesn&rsquo;t directly affect mortgage qualifying mechanics. We document the funding stage and lead investor for context but qualify on actual W-2 + equity + secondary sale documentation. Tier-1 VC participation may support balance sheet narrative for Jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company just completed a tender offer for founder + employee liquidity. How is that documented?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Tender offers (company-organized periodic events allowing founder and early-employee share sales) at established late-stage private companies document liquidity capacity. We document the tender offer through company-provided documentation showing the offered price, founder participation, proceeds amount, and use-of-proceeds elections. The completed tender offer supports balance sheet narrative and any Asset-Depletion path on resulting liquid balance.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m post-IPO with stock in lockup. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Post-IPO lockup (typically 6 months post-IPO restricting founder and early-employee stock sales) delays liquidity availability. During lockup, we qualify on continuing W-2 employment at the IPO&rsquo;d company. Post-lockup expiration, stock sale liquidity becomes available for Asset-Depletion path on liquid reserves. We coordinate timing with lockup expiration.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My company is structured as a Delaware C-corp. Does that matter?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Delaware C-corp incorporation is standard for VC-funded startups due to Delaware corporate law and Section 1202 QSBS eligibility. Delaware incorporation doesn&rsquo;t directly affect mortgage qualifying but supports the company narrative. We document the incorporation state through corporate documentation if relevant for any specific qualifying narrative.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for entrepreneurs?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Some lenders offer founder-focused programs that accommodate non-traditional income structures. What matters most is finding a broker who understands founder channel-specific qualifying: B3-3.3-02 Schedule C with Form 1084 addbacks for bootstrapped, B3-3.4-02 S-corp / partnership with entity-level Form 1084 for structured, B3-3.1-01 VC-funded W-2 with equity documentation, B3-3.1-09 continuing earnout sources, and Asset-Depletion Non-QM for post-exit. Conventional Conforming, Jumbo, and Non-QM done right outperforms specialty product chasing.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use bank statements alone instead of tax returns?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes through Bank Statement Program Non-QM for high-deduction bootstrapped founders. 12 or 24 months of business bank statements qualify under the Bank Statement framework. Useful when Schedule C / S-corp deductions are substantial enough that Form 1084 addbacks alone don&rsquo;t produce desired qualifying income. Pricing carries 0.75-1.5% rate premium vs Conventional.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My PE-backed acquirer offered me rollover equity in the acquirer entity. How is that treated?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Rollover equity in PE-acquired company holding entity qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-09</a> when vesting schedule produces continuing income. We document the rollover equity grant terms, vesting schedule, and any current valuation. PE-backed rollover equity has less liquidity than publicly traded RSU but documents continuing equity participation narrative.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I just raised a Series A round. My W-2 doesn&rsquo;t have 2-year history yet. How can I qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Recent transitions from bootstrapped founder to VC-funded founder-CEO create new-employment underwriting where the new W-2 doesn&rsquo;t yet have 2 years. Strategic options: (1) qualify on prior bootstrapped Schedule C / S-corp history if recent and adequate; (2) wait 12-24 months to establish new W-2 history; (3) co-borrower file with spouse income providing stability; (4) Bank Statement Non-QM on prior business operating history.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 120-150 days before you intend to make an offer. Founder files benefit from substantial runway because of channel-specific qualifying (Schedule C vs S-corp K-1 vs VC-funded W-2 vs post-exit Asset-Depletion), multi-year entity returns documentation, Form 1084 cash-flow addback analysis, equity vesting documentation, possible coordination with anticipated exit timing or tender offer cycles, and any Section 1202 QSBS documentation if relevant.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What HR or company documentation should I request?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For bootstrapped founders: 1099-NECs, Schedule C / S-corp 1120-S with all worksheets, business bank statements, K-1s if S-corp or partnership. For VC-funded founder-CEOs: HR letter covering W-2 + bonus history, equity grant documentation with vesting schedule, board approval for any compensation changes. For pre-IPO with secondary sales: tender offer documentation showing offered price and participation; secondary marketplace transaction confirmations. For post-exit: acquisition agreement with earnout schedule, rollover equity grant terms, brokerage statements showing liquid balance, Section 1202 QSBS documentation through CPA.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

