<Layout title="Entrepreneur &amp; Founder Mortgage · Bootstrapped Schedule C, S-Corp Founder K-1, VC-Funded Founder-CEO W-2 + Equity, Pre-IPO Secondary Sales, Section 1202 QSBS Exit &amp; Post-Exit Asset-Depletion Specialist" description="Entrepreneur and founder mortgage for bootstrapped sole proprietor founders with Schedule C 1099 income from sole prop or single-member LLC (default Schedule C) earning $100K-$500K with substantial deductions for office, software platforms, contractor payments, business development, and travel, bootstrapped S-corp founders with Form 1120-S combining W-2 reasonable compensation $120K-$200K plus K-1 distributions from remaining net business income, partnership founders with multi-member LLC Form 1065 K-1 distributions, VC-funded founder-CEOs at Series A through D companies with elevated W-2 base salary ($200K-$400K typical at Series A-B, $300K-$500K at Series C-D, $400K-$800K at late-stage unicorn tier) plus 4-year equity vesting schedule with 1-year cliff plus pre-IPO secondary share sale liquidity through tender offers (company-organized) and secondary marketplaces including Forge Global, EquityZen, and Carta, late-stage founder-CEOs at unicorn-tier private companies (valuation $1B+) with elevated W-2 plus substantial unrealized equity value plus established secondary share sale opportunities, post-exit founders following acquisition by strategic acquirer or PE buyer with cash proceeds plus multi-year earnout payment schedule (1-3 years post-close) plus rollover equity in acquirer entity, post-IPO founders following Initial Public Offering with stock sale liquidity subject to lockup expiration (6 months post-IPO typical) plus continuing W-2 employment, and Section 1202 QSBS founder-stock exits at C-corp incorporation companies under $50M gross assets at stock issuance held 5+ years producing up to $10M (or 10x basis if higher) of capital gain tax-free per IRC Section 1202. Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 variable income with 24-month average for VC-funded founder-CEO W-2, B3-3.1-09 other sources for continuing earnout and rollover equity vesting, B3-3.3-02 self-employed Schedule C analysis with Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks for bootstrapped solo founders, B3-3.4-02 partnership and S-corporation analysis for S-corp and partnership founders with Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks at entity level. Conventional Conforming, Conventional Jumbo, Conventional Super-Jumbo, S-Corp Self-Employed, Schedule C + Form 1084, Bank Statement Non-QM (high-deduction bootstrapped), Asset-Depletion Non-QM (post-exit founder with substantial liquid reserves), and P&amp;L Statement Only Non-QM (recent rapid-growth founder) loan program options. CRITICAL: Section 1202 QSBS (Qualified Small Business Stock) under IRC Section 1202 allows up to $10M (or 10x basis if higher) of capital gain tax-free on qualifying C-corp founder stock held 5+ years (C-corp under $50M gross assets at issuance, qualifying trade or business excluding service businesses, hotels, restaurants, banks, farms). Substantial tax-advantaged structure for founder exits combined with Florida no-state-income-tax advantage. Section 1202 QSBS awareness expanding, post-2022 down rounds and valuation correction, AI startup wave 2023-2025 driving new founder cohort, secondary marketplace development (Forge Global, EquityZen, Carta), PE consolidation acquiring growth-stage companies, and Florida tech ecosystem growth in Miami (Wynwood, Brickell), Tampa, and Orlando with notable companies including Chewy (NYSE: CHWY, Plantation-based) and Magic Leap industry dynamics." canonical="https://stairwaymortgage.com/professional-services/entrepreneurs/">
